06113nam a2200805Ia 9780520972131DE-B159720240602123719.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240602t20202020cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209721317 a10.1525/97805209721312doi  a(DE-B1597)567842  a(OCoLC)1154896369  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 7aPOL0080002bisacsh04a324.9731 aCampbell, W. Joseph, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLost in a Gallup :bPolling Failure in U.S. Presidential Elections /cW. Joseph Campbell. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (336 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Figures, Tables, and Boxes -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Of Pollsters, Journalists, and Presidential Elections -- t1. Of Poll-Bashing Journalists and the “Babe Ruth” of Survey Research -- t2. “A Time of Polls Gone Mad”: The Literary Digest Debacle of 1936 -- t3. “The Defeat of the Pollsters”: The Epic Fail of 1948 -- t4. A Tie “Would Suit Them Fine”: The 1952 Landslide Pollsters Did Not Foresee -- t5. The “Close Race That Never Happened”: Miscalling the 1980 Election -- t6. “Television’s Version of ‘Dewey Defeats Truman’”: The Trifecta of 2000 -- t7. “President Kerry”: Exit Polls Misfire in 2004 -- t8. “Gallup vs. the World”: Pointing the Wrong Way in 2012 -- t9. “The Night That Wasn’t Supposed to Happen”: The Shock Election of 2016 -- tConclusion: Will It Happen Again? -- tNotes -- tSelect Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA sweeping look at the messy and contentious past of US presidential pre-election polls and why they aren’t as reliable as we think. Polls in U.S. presidential elections can and do get it wrong—as surprising outcomes in 2020, in 2016, in 2012, in 2004, in 2000 all remind us. Lost in a Gallup captures in lively and unprecedented fashion the stories of polling flops, epic upsets, unforeseen landslides, and exit poll fiascoes in presidential elections since 1936. Polling’s checkered record in elections has rarely been considered in detail and, until now, has never been addressed collectively. Polling embarrassments are not all alike. Pollsters have anticipated tight elections when landslides occurred; they have indicated the wrong winner in closer elections; state polls have confounded expected national outcomes. Exit polling has thrown Election Day into confusion. The work of venerable pollsters has been singularly and memorably in error. It is a rare presidential election not to be marred by polling controversies. Lost in a Gallup casts a critical eye on major figures in election polling such as George Gallup, a prickly founding father of public opinion research. The book also considers the polling innovations of Warren Mitofsky, whose admonition rings true across generations: “There’s a lot of room for humility in polling. Every time you get cocky, you lose.” Lost in a Gallup examines how polling failure often equates to journalistic failure. Historically, poll-bashing was quite pronounced among prominent journalists, including well-known newspaper columnists such as Mike Royko in Chicago and Jimmy Breslin in New York. They and other journalists challenged the presumption that polls could accurately measure or interpret what the public was thinking. Even so, polls drive news media narratives about presidential elections, shaping conventional wisdom about how competitive those races are. As Lost in a Gallup makes clear, polls are not always in error. But when they fail, they can fail in surprising ways.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aElectionszUnited StatesxHistory. 0aPolitical campaignszUnited Stat